            <h2>Introduction to Strong Verbs</h2>
            <p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">I</span>n addition to Weak Verbs and Irregular Verbs, Old
                English also has a large category of verbs called <strong>Strong Verbs</strong>. Unlike Weak Verbs, which form
                their past tense by adding a <strong>-d</strong> or <strong>-t</strong> before the suffix (ending), Strong Verbs
                form their past tense by changing their root vowel. 
            </p>
                <p>This is very similar to the difference between weak and strong verbs
                in modern English: the past tense of the weak verb 'walk' is 'walk<strong>ed</strong>'; the past tense of the strong verb 'wr<strong>i</strong>te' is 'wr<strong>o</strong>te'.
                In the first example, an -ed ending is added; in the second example, there is a change to the vowel from 'i' to 'o' to indicate the past tense.
                </p>
                <p>Old English strong verbs also change their vowel to form the past tense. For example, examine the verb 'drincan' in the following sentences: 
                '<em>He drincþ of ðæm wine - He drinks the wine</em>' and '<em>He dranc of ðæm wine - He drank the wine</em>'.
                </p>
